==Old English==

===Etymology===
From an Indo-European root ''*(s)kel-'' ‘shall, must, owe’.  Cognate with Old High German [[scolan]] (German [[sollen]]), Old Saxon [[skulan]] (Dutch [[zullen]]), Old Norse [[skulu]] (Swedish [[skola]]), Gothic [[𐍃𐌺𐌿𐌻𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'ʃʊlan/

===Verb===
'''sculan''' (preterite-present verb: 1st-person singular present '''sceal''', 2nd-person singular present '''scealt''', present plural '''sculon''', preterite singular '''sceolde''')
====Transitive====
# to [[owe]]
====Auxiliary====
# to be obliged to do something; [[must]]
# expressing the speaker’s intention to do something
# going to; to be about to

